<div class="quotetitle">tokumaru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br /><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I just subtract $10 every frame<br /></div><br />What about fading in? You start from black and compare against the target values every frame? Where are the target values stored?</div><br />If a 32-byte update slot is open:<br />1. Query the level and all on-screen objects for their palette, storing the result in that update slot<br />2. Run the fade routine on that update slot with $10, $20, or $30<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">This also allows a distinction in the palette between $20, which is ordinary white, and $30, which shows up as superbright white during fades.<br /></div><br />Are you saying that we should avoid $30 just like we avoid $0D?</div><br />No, just use it sparingly for when you need something to be just that bright.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Thu Nov 10, 2011 11:51 am</p><hr />
